---
title: Particle Float
description: Floating particles using multiple elements with staggered CSS `animation-delay` values.
slug: particle-float
cssFile: particle-float.css
explanation: "Each particle is a small `<div>` with `position: absolute` and `border-radius: 50%`. The `@keyframes` animation moves them from the bottom to the top of the container (`translateY`) while fading in and out via `opacity`. `animation-delay` offsets each particle's start time, and varying `animation-duration` values create different speeds — giving the illusion of independent movement from a single keyframe definition."
---
{% extends "example.njk" %}
{% block demo %}
<div class="particle-stage">
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
	<div class="particle"></div>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block html_code %}
{%- highlight "html" %}
<div class="particle-stage">
  <div class="particle"></div>
  <div class="particle"></div>
  <!-- repeat 10–20 times -->
</div>
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}

{% block css_code %}
{%- highlight "css" %}
.particle {
  position: absolute;
  border-radius: 50%;
  animation: particle-rise linear infinite;
  opacity: 0;
}

.particle:nth-child(1) {
  left: 8%; width: 6px; height: 6px;
  background: var(--accent);
  animation-duration: 4s;
  animation-delay: 0s;
}
/* more nth-child variations... */

@keyframes particle-rise {
  0%   { transform: translateY(240px); opacity: 0; }
  10%  { opacity: .8; }
  100% { transform: translateY(-20px); opacity: 0; }
}
{%- endhighlight %}
{% endblock %}
